Iel wondered if she would invite him in, unlike the other times when iel had asked. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory giggled at the memory. Kari had thrown a book at his shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A single knock came from inside, which seemed to mean she was there, but after all, where else could she have been?
"May I come in?", asked Ivory, remembering the time when iel had entered without asking for permission.
Un coup retentit de l'intérieur. It seemed to want to say yes. Ivory shivered, from cold, but also because of the noise. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a room supposed to be empty, even though she had entered this room for years.
"Here I am," said Ivory, opening the door slowly. The scene inside the room was unusual, according to the standards of normal people, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statues were scattered around. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was colder than the rest of the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have fallen inside.
The girl who was there was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her blanket, reading one of her notebooks.
"Which notebook is it?" asked Ivory, sitting down next to Kari on her bed.
